  "articleSummary": "**Summary**  \nThearticle argues that “just adding more engineers” never speeds up a late software project because communication overhead grows quadratically with team size (n (n‑1)/2), quickly dwarfing any gain in raw capacity. It cites studies from Microsoft, *Accelerate*, and IEEE showing that larger teams suffer higher coordination costs, longer onboarding times (3‑6 months for senior engineers), and more interruptions, all of which delay deadlines. The piece reinforces Brooks’s Law with modern examples—CI/CD, microservices, and Amazon’s two‑pizza rule—showing that while tooling has improved, the fundamental math of human collaboration has not. The tone is a data‑driven rant aimed at engineering managers, CTOs, and project leaders who might be tempted to “scale up” to meet delivery dates.",
